# gen133 (T-series rule grammar): CONJUNCTIVE concepts. "every friendly dog is a
# goodboy" learns a multi-condition rule goodboy(X) :- friendly(X), dog(X) (the
# engine always supported multi-goal bodies; gen133 adds the intake + an
# article-free way to assert the adjectival conjuncts). This single capability
# unlocks the conjunctive cases the recent generations promised — abduction over
# several premises (gen131/132) and MULTI-fact robustness (gen130's open edge).

# The modifiers before the head noun become conjoined premises.
> every friendly dog is a goodboy
< Learned rule: goodboy(X) :- friendly(X), dog(X).

# One conjunct supplied (noun, with article); the goal is not yet provable.
> rex is a dog
< Learned: dog(rex).
> is rex a goodboy?
< No.

# Abduction names only the MISSING conjunct, while reporting the full rule.
> what would make rex a goodboy?
< If you told me that rex is a friendly, then rex would be a goodboy — that's the rule friendly and dog -> goodboy.

# The other conjunct asserted ARTICLE-FREE ("rex is friendly") — accepted only
# because 'friendly' is a class a rule already depends on — and gen103's
# self-correction fires across the conjunctive rule.
> rex is friendly
< Learned: friendly(rex). Now rex is a goodboy after all.
> is rex a goodboy?
< Yes.

# gen130 robustness, now with the conjunctive case it could not reach before:
# BOTH facts are load-bearing.
> how robust is that conclusion?
< My conclusion that rex is a goodboy rests on 2 load-bearing facts: dog(rex), friendly(rex). Removing any one would overturn it.
